{
  "description": {
    "title": "One-way price link A -> B (recursive/block-recursive partial equilibrium)",
    "economic_framing": "A large REFERENCE carbon market (ETS_ref) and a smaller LINKED market (ETS_link). A firm in the linked market abates through a fuel-switching technology whose cost rises with the reference carbon price (e.g. the switch competes for the same low-carbon fuel priced off the reference market). The coupling is ONE-WAY: the reference price drives the linked market's abatement cost, but the linked market is too small to feed back into the reference price. This is a recursive (block-recursive) partial equilibrium -- solved once in topological order, no fixed-point iteration.",
    "mechanism": "ETS_ref clears competitively at P_ref = sigma*(E0 - Q_ref) = 2*(100 - Q_ref); as its cap Q_ref declines 60->55->50 the reference price rises 80->90->100. The mac_cost link A->B (phi=0.5) lifts the linked market's threshold block cost to c_B + phi*P_ref, and the interior linked market pins there: P_link = 10 + 0.5*P_ref = 50->55->60. ETS_ref is UNAFFECTED by ETS_link (upstream invariance): its solved price is byte-identical with or without the outgoing link.",
    "expected_output": {
      "P_ref 2026-2028 [USD/tCO2]": [80.0, 90.0, 100.0],
      "P_link 2026-2028 [USD/tCO2]": [50.0, 55.0, 60.0],
      "Link A->B mac_cost Input Shift 2026-2028 [USD/tCO2]": [40.0, 45.0, 50.0],
      "reading": "The linked market's price is exactly c_B + phi*P_ref each year -- the transmission is inert-as-mechanism (P_link is what a standalone market with a hand-shifted threshold would give) but meaningful-as-information (it carries the reference price into the linked market's cost). A never sees B; the acyclic run stamps no Joint* columns."
    }
  },
